One of the milestones of 2022 was joining the #WidexCanada team as their #SoundAmbassador. 

These past few months have helped me appreciate even more my sense of hearing, and treat with more empathy people around me who may be experiencing hearing loss.

Unfortunately, sigma still surrounds the use of hearing aids, preventing a large number of people from wearing them -- something we want to change with the team at #WidexCanada.

If you or someone you know is dealing with a hearing issue, don't hesitate to talk to a hearing professional. Visit www.widex.com/en-ca to get started.

While headphones and earbuds present a potential danger of hearing loss, they aren’t completely bad for your ears. It just depends on how you use them.

If you simply can’t live without them, some audiologists recommend sticking to the 60/60 rule: set the volume of your headphones to 60% and only listen to music for short periods of 60 minutes.

Remember that listening to anything above 85 decibels, as well as loudly for extended periods can cause damage to your hearing over time.

Something that I’ve learned over the years is to properly care for my ears and my hearing when planning for a concert or festival. Loud noise can
damage your hearing – and cost you more than your ticket!

Here are 4 tips from #WidexCanada for minimizing the risk of hearing loss after a concert:

1. Don’t stand close to the loudspeakers
2. Use earplugs for concerts – and do it correctly. You can even get hearing protection that’s shaped for your ears and doesn’t compromise the music and sound experience
3. Take quiet breaks away from the loud music – it’s important to rest your ears after a lot of strain
4. Act in time – the second you feel that the sound is distorted, or you hear a crunching in your ears, move away from the sound or use your earplugs.

Hey musicians, hear me out: that ringing in your ears after a performance isn’t hearing loss, but it could be an early indicator of things to come. Musicians are 57% more likely to develop tinnitus than other people. Many rock musicians, for instance, develop tinnitus from playing loudly long before they realize they’ve lost hearing in one or both ears. The high likelihood among musicians of developing tinnitus should be an opportunity to seek the counsel of an audiologist, many of whom specialize in treating musicians.

#HearingHealth #WidexSoundAmbassador

Have you noticed a “blind side” in your hearing? Some musicians begin to lose hearing in only one ear due to direct exposure on the side they hold their instrument or in the case of an orchestra, for being seated in a section where they receive direct sound from the horns in one ear. To combat this effect, some orchestras furnish certain musicians with neck shields to reduce noise exposure from louder instruments. #HearingHealth #WidexSoundAmbassador @WidexCanada

I'm part of a group working on a documentary about the Spirit of Radio years of CFNY-FM/Toronto (now known as The Edge), that period between 1978 and 1992 when the station was part of the birth and rise of alternative music. 

Here’s where you might come in. We have reserved shooting days in June for fans to tell their CFNY stories. If you have an A+ story involving your experience with the station (good or bad) between 1978 and 1992, let me know. Basically, we’re looking for superfans.

If that’s you, send a quick description of your story to alan@alancross.ca and put “CFNY Story” in the subject line. We’ll collect them all and pick the top few. Those people will then be called in to tell their stories on camera.

We’re in the final throes of production for the long-in-the-making documentary about CFNY-FM/Toronto (now 102.1 The Edge) with a focus on the station’s influential “Spirit of Radio Years” (1977-1992-ish). All that’s left is to shoot some B-roll, a bunch of editing, license the music–and gather some video testimonials from fans.

If you were a CFNY fan back in those years, get out your smartphone and send us a selfie video and you might end up seeing yourself over the ending credits of the documentary when it’s released in 2024.

All the details of what we need from you can be found here: https://www.ajournalofmusicalthings.com/want-to-be-in-the-cfny-spirit-of-radio-documentary-heres-how/

You can also reach out to me directly via email through alan@alancross.ca
